\fs22 CSS best practices\ulnone\b0\par
We will find below an excerpt of CSS best practices that were written by Elika J. Etemad (also known as fantasai). Elika is an expert on the W3C CSS Working Group (since 2004) and a longtime contributor on the Mozilla Proejct. In addition to editing many of the CSS3 specifications, she's worked on layout engine testing and development for Gecko and managing the CSS test suites at W3C.\par
\par
\b Executive Summary\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1\b Logical source order\b0 : The order of the HTML content should make sense even without CSS: for accessibility, mobile optimization, device adaptability and long-term maintainability\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b Liquid layouts and relativity:\b0  Use smart relative sizing: to optimize layouts while minimizing media query code forks.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b Media queries:\b0  Adapt to screen size changes; get font size adaptation free by using ems\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b Prevent zombie code:\b0  Dead code may come alive as CSS changes. It should be deleted before it does and ruins the layout.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b Test in multiple browsers:\b0  Our favourite browser isn't always right\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b Do not use proprietary features:\b0  We should keep the web open to everyone and not rely and the latest -WebKit- invention\par
