\ul\b The W3C CSS WG\ulnone\b0\par
The CSS Working Group is a working group created by W3C in 1997 to tackle issues that had not been addressed with CSS level 1. The number of members reaches 125 in April 2017.\par
\par
The CSS WG members are working on a whole range of specifications, but their core document is CSS snapshot 2017. This document collects together into one definition all the specs that together form the current state of Cascading Style Sheets as of 2017. The primary audience is CSS implementers, not CSS authors, as this definition includes modules by specification stability, not Web browser adoption rate.\par
\par
\ul\b\fs28 5.2 - The basics of design\ulnone\b0\par
\ul\b\fs22 Applying basic design principals\ulnone\b0\par
Often it's hard to pull apart the pieces of a design that are "good" or "bad", most of that is subjective. Instead, it's better to think of indivitual pieces of a design as "effective" or "ineffective" according to the demographic and the task they are trying to achieve.\par
\par
Web sites can become pretty complicated if we add many design elements, and it can be intimidating to figure out how to get started when thinking about how to present our Web page. One of the best ways to get started is to think about each individual HTML elements we've learned how to style so far, and how to style according to our specific goals.\par
\par
In this module, we'll discuss how to style the three most fundamental design aspects of a Web page: typography, color, and white space.\par
\par
\ul\b Typography\ulnone\b0\par
A good rule of thumb when designing our Web site is to use no more than two different typefaces per page. Typically this means that we select 1 bold typeface for titles or other eye-catching pieces of text, and a neutral typeface for large blocks or body text of our page.\par
\par
There is no official taxonomy of fonts, and not all browsers support all fonts, so it can be difficult to get our font looking exactly the way we want on all platforms. While we're starting out, it's best to stick to the most popular and commonly used fonts. In the link between the parens is a good list of fonts for English pages and the appropriate fall-backs to get us started ({{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/Style/Examples/007/fonts.en.html }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/Style/Examples/007/fonts.en.html\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 ). On the Web, we can find other lists of available system fonts for non-Latin scripts.\par
\par
As we get more comfortable, we can branch out to more exotic fonts. We should remember that, when we are building our font-family set, we will want to always include a Web safe font alternative for an exotic font in case the user's device doesn't support it.\par
\par
When choosing our font, probably the biggest choice we'll make is the category of font to use. There are 5 basic categories of font:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1\b sans-serif:\b0  These are the most popular fonts for Web pages. This means the letters do not have added flourishes, so the typefaces are simpler. Their simplicity makes them easier to display on computer screens as their resolution is much lower than a printed document. It is often suggested we choose a sans-serif font for large blocks of digital text\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}serif:\b0  These fonts are the second most popular typefaces. "Serif" refers to the small flourish lines at the edges of letters and symbols. "Serifs" make each character more distinct, making text easier to read in print. This is why these fonts might remind us of a text from a typewriter, or of the fonts we see in printed books, newspapers or magazines. These typefaces can often be used effectively for titles or emphasis.\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}monospace:\b0  These fonts guarantee that all letters have the same fixed width. This is similar to a manual typewriter, or how computer code appears in editors.  These fonts were designed for the ease of the technology, not humans, so they should be used sparingly. The most effective time to use these is when showing snippets of code\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}cursive:\b0  These fonts mimic human handwriting often by joining letter or having an italic slant. For some languages, these fonts are extra effective such as Arabic. Often than for specific languages, these fonts in English can be rather complex so they are best use extremely sparingly\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}fantasy:\b0  This is the most diverse category of fonts and includes all of those that are particularly decorative. These can really great top headers as they can give our Web page a very distinct visual identity. Rarely will we want ot use these for anything other than titles. It is also good to note that few of these are widely supported, so to use these we'll probably want to download them from a font service to make them available for our user\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
External resource\b0\par
W3C documentation for all of CSS's font properties: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/TR/css-fonts-3/ }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/TR/css-fonts-3/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
\par
\ul\b Color\ulnone\b0\par
One of the most important design decisions we can make is our Web site's color palette. We should choose a palette before we begin designing to keep a cohesive visual identity. A common mistake is to use too many colors on a page. As we are starting out, it is best to limit ourselves to just a few colors per page.\par
\par
For a consistent look and feel our users will recognize, we will want ot limit ourselves to around 4 colors for all non-graphic content like text, backgrounds, borders, etc. There are different color palette tools on the Web we can play around with, but one of the best ways is to find a site we like the look and feel and see if we can identify what color palette they are using.\par
\par
When getting into design, it's good idea to brush up on the basics of color theory, but just in case here's a short refresher.\par
\par
\b Colors make other colors\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 The historical color wheel is organized around the three primary colors: red, yellow and blue\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 The secondary colors are the combinations of these primary colors: orange, green and purple\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 We can follow this pattern of varying the amount if each primary color to create infinite intermediary colors\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 However, as we've seen for the web, we define all colors as combinations of red, green and blue. The short answer for this is because that is how the human eye perceives color, something that was unknown when the historical color wheel was made\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
Build a palette based on the color wheel\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Colors that are across the wheel are called "complementary", blue and orange, red and green, etc\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Colors that are next to one another are considered "analogous" like navy, blue and teal, or lime, green and hunter\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 When picking a color palette, we should generally pick between one that is comprised mostly of analogous colors, or mostly complementary colors. Thankfully, there are lots of wonderful tools to help us do this. One very good is paletton.com, where we can choose a starting color. It will generate for us a set of other colors that according to color theory will look pleasing together.\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b0 In our 4 colors, we'll want to keep a consistent tone so that our colors look good together. We'll want at least 1 very light color and 1 dark color. Avoid having all dark color or all light, as often having contrast is important for readibility. Also keep in mind not all users have full-color vision, so we should try ot avoid too many similar colors. We will discuss how to choose inclusive color in more detail in a later section.\par
\par
\b External resource\b0\par
Here is a good article that goes into detail about color theory: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/wiki/Colour_theory }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/wiki/Colour_theory\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
\par
\ul\b White space\ulnone\b0\par
It can be difficult to strike a good balance of white space. The most common mistake beginner Web designers make it to not leave enough white space or empty space between HTML elements.\par
\par
We will want to make liberal use of paddings and margins to make sure that our site has plenty of empty space. Empty space makes it easier for a user's eyes to move around our page. We will want to ensure there is space between our HTML elements as well as between our elements and the edge of the page.\par
\par
Good balance between content and white space prevents our user from becoming fatigued while looking at our site. For example, when lines of text are very long, it is difficult to read without losing track of where we are. It is also fatiguing when the lines of text are too short because the user has to read vertically too much. There is considerable research on the topic, but a good rule of thumb is to limit lines of text to 50-75 characters wide.\par
\par
