\ul\fs28 5.3 - Designing for our audience\ulnone\b0\par
\ul\b\fs22 Intro to Web accessibility\ulnone\b0\par
\i The power of the Web is in its universality.\par
Access by everyone regardless of disability is an essential aspect.\i0\par
\b Tim Berners-Lee\b0\par
\par
The Web has become an essential aspect of our daily lives, and everyone should have access to this technology. Web accessibility focuses on ensuring equivalent access for people with disabilities. It is increasingly important to many organizations and governments from around the world, and has many business benefits. Access to information, including on the Web, is also recognized by the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.\par
\par
\b Who is impacted?\b0\par
Web accessibility addresses all dissabilities, including hearing, learning and cognitive, neurological, physical, speech, and visual disabilities. Some examples of Web accessibility features include:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Captions on audio and multimedia content for people who are hard of hearing\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Clear and consistent layout for people with learning and cognitive disabilities\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Keyboard support for people with physical disabilities and do not use a mouse\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Text alternatives for people with visual disabilities and using screen readers\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
Web accessibility benefits people with and without disabilities\b0\line Web accessibility features also benefit many more users, such as:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 People with temporal situational limitations, such as a broken arm\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 People using mobile devices, televisions and other access channels\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 People using older computers, with low bandwidth and other limitations\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 People who are new to computers, to the Web, or to our own website\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 People who are not fluent in the language of our particular website\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b0 The Web is an increasingly important resource in many aspects of life: education, employment, government, commerce, health care, recreation and many more. When Web pages, Web technologies, Web tools, or Web applications are badly designed, they can create barriers that exclude people from using the Web. More information is available in the W3C Accessibility overview( {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/standards/webdesign/accessibility }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/standards/webdesign/accessibility\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 )\par
\b\par
\par
First steps in Web accessibility\b0\par
There are many simple Web accessibility improvements that we can implement and check right away, even when we're new to this topic. Two example excerpts are provided below on this page but we can find more tips and information from W3C/WAI:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Tips for Getting Started with Web Accessibility ( {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/WAI/gettingstarted/tips/ }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/WAI/gettingstarted/tips/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 )\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Easy Checks - A First Review of Web Accessibility ( {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/WAI/eval/preliminary }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/WAI/eval/preliminary\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 )\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
Example 1: page title\b0\par
Good page titles are particularly important for orientation - to help people know where they are and move between pages open in their browser. The first thing screen readers say when the user goes to a different web page is the page title. In the Web page markup, they are the <title> within the <head>\par
\par
Check #1: There is a title that adequately and briefly describes the content of a page, and that it distinguishes the page from other Web pages\par
\par
<head>\par
\tab <title>Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI) - home page</title>\par
</head>\par
\par
\b Example 2: image text alternatives ("ALT TEXT")\b0\par
Text alternatives are a primary way of making visual information accessible, because they can be rendered through any sensory modality (for example, visual, auditory or tactile) to match the needs of the user. Providing text alternatives allows the information to be rendered in a variety of ways by a variety of user agents. For example, a person who cannot see a picture can have the text alternative read aloud using synthesized speech.\par
\par
