\ul\b Inclusive design\ulnone\b0\par
As we are designing our site, it is critical that we keep in mind the range of users who might be viewing the page. There are some simple design choices we can make to ensure that our web page is as inclusive as possible.\par
\par
Typically a good approach is to keep our designs on the simpler side. Not only is this in line with current trends, but when there are fewer elements and styles, it is easier for everyone to consume the information we are trying to convoy.\par
\par
\b color-blind\b0\par
When a user is color-blind, it typically means there is a category of colors that are difficult for them to distinguish between. So, by picking diverse colors that contrast well, we can ensure that these users can still read our page. To do this:\par

\pard 
{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Pick a base color (example: blue)\b\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}\b0 Choose one or two shades of the same color as supplementary colors. Make sure these colors contrast with the base color, meaning that if one was placed on top of the other, it is still legible. Also, if we are choosing multiple supplementary colors, we should try to pick one from the yellows group (warmer colors) and one from the blues group (cooler colors). This way, a color-blind user is likely to only have difficulty seeing one of these, not both\b\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}\b0 Select an accent color that is a totally different color from the previously chosen colors\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b0 Even with a carefully chosen palette, it might still be difficult for a user to distinguish between colors. In addition to using color to indicate something, we'll also want to use shape. For example, if we have two buttons, one that is green for "agree" and one that is red for "disagree", it can be almost impossible for some users to decide which to click. In this case, we'll want to make sure they are both clearly labeled, or the shapes of the buttons are distinctly different.\par
\par
Thankfully, the Paciello Group has created a tool we can download to check if our chosen colors provide enough contrast for color blind users. We can find out more about this free tool here: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.paciellogroup,con/resources/contrastanalyser/ }}{\fldrslt{https://www.paciellogroup,con/resources/contrastanalyser/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
\par
\b low-vision\b0\par
It is extremely common (as many as 20% of users over 45) for a user to have difficulty reading small text. These users often will have their Web browser set to magnify text to a size that is more comfortable for them, which can make all carefully designed layouts look very different. These users will typically do one of two things:\par

\pard 
{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 zoom in on the entire page: we can test to see what this experience will be like with our own Web browser, typically with the Ctrl + shortcut\b\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}\b0 use a text-only zoom: to see what it looks like, we might want to text our layout with larger fonts, like 24pt or 32pt, to make sure our layout can grow to accomodate the overflow text. Also, we should note that long lines of text (over 50 characters wide) can be especially difficult to scroll through to read\b\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b0 In general, we will want to make sure our font size is at least 1em. By using em we can let the text size grow based on the user's browser settings.\par
\par
\ul\b What is internationalization?\ulnone\b0\par
Access to the Web for all has been a fundamental concern and goal of the W3C since the beginning. It is easy to overlook the needs of people from cultures different to our own, or who use different languages or writing systems, but we have to ensure that any content or application that we design or develop is ready to support the international features that they will need.\par
\line Internationalization is sometimes abbreviated to 'i18n' in English, because there are 18 characters between the 'i' and the 'n'..\par
\line The W3C Internationalizaiton Activity works with W3C working groups and liases with other organizations to make it possible to use Web technologies with different languages, scripts, and cultures.\par
\par
People who use non-Latin writing systems or use the Latin script for certain languages, often have specific typographic needs that differ from text in, say, English. As we learn more about CSS, we will find that it provides many features to support those needs.\par
\par
Whereas HTML markup provides structure for the content of our page, CSS brings the expressive power to make the page look the way a person from particular culture would expect.\par
\par
\b Examples\b0\par
Here are some examples of things that can be done with CSS.\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 It is already possible to make text run vertically in CSS for languages such as Chinese, Japanese, Korean and Mongolian. For more information, we can consult the following page: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/International/articles/vertical-text/ }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/International/articles/vertical-text/\ul0\cf0}}}}\b\f0\fs22\line\b0 We can also style conters for lists or chapter headings and such like according to local preferences.\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 When we want to justify text so that lines are straight on both sides of our column, different strategies are used for different scripts. Most Western typography pust an emphasis on adjusting inter-word spaces, but Chinese don't use spaces between words, so we generally do inter-character spacing. In text written using the arabic script it is common to stretch the baseline that joins letters, or use other techniques to balance the line.\b\line\b0 Some scripts allow words to be hyphenated in order to improve the visual effect of a paragraph\b\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\b0 Text decoration and text style features can vary in applicability from script to script. For example, Japanese characters are fairly complicated so, rather than italicise their text for emphasis, which can make it harder to read at small sizes, they have a tradition of placing special marks alongside the emphasised text. Also, it may be important to avoid underlines running over descenders in some scripts, since itg can obscure important marks attached to a base character, so CSS allows us to skip "ink" as shown in the Burmese example on the page.\b\par

